SIMPLE: map
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Map
<hw>Map</hw> <pr>(m⟦acr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From F.
<ets>mappe</ets>, in <ets>mappemonde</ets> map of the world, fr. L.
<ets>mappa</ets> napkin, signal cloth; -- a Punic word. Cf.
<er>Apron</er>, <er>Napkin</er>, <er>Nappe</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A representation of the surface of the earth, or of some portion of
it, showing the relative position of the parts represented; -- usually
on a flat surface. Also, such a representation of the celestial sphere,
or of some part of it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ There are five principal kinds of projection used in
making maps: the <xex>orthographic</xex>, the <xex>stereographic</xex>,
the <xex>globuar</xex>, the <xex>conical</xex>, and the
<xex>cylindrical</xex>, or <xex>Mercator's projection</xex>. See
<er>Projection</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A graphical representation of anything showing the
relative arrangement of its parts in a maplike form.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything which represents graphically a succession
of events, states, or acts; <as>as, an historical
<ex>map</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus is his cheek the <qex>map</qex> of days outworn.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mathematics)</fld> <def>A relation between two sets
in which an element of one set is associated with each element of the
other set. Also called a <asp>mapping</asp>, <asp>transformation</asp>,
or <asp>correspondence</asp>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Map lichen</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a lichen
(<spn>Lecidea geographica</spn>.) growing on stones in curious maplike
figures.</cd> <rj><au>Dr. Prior.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Map</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Map
<hw>Map</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mapped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mapping</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To represent by a
map; -- often with <xex>out</xex>; <as>as, to survey and <ex>map</ex>,
or <ex>map out</ex>, a <ex>county</ex></as>. Hence, figuratively: To
represent or indicate systematically and clearly; to sketch; to plan;
<as>as, to <ex>map</ex>, or <ex>map out</ex>, a journey; to <ex>map
out</ex> business.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am near to the place where they should meet, if Pisanio have
<qex>mapped</qex> it truly.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mathematics)</fld> <def>To create a mapping between
two sets; see <er>map</er>{4}, <pos>n.</pos>. Also, to create any list
of corresponding elements of two sets of things; <as>as, to <ex>map</ex>
the symbols of an ancient language into a modern phonetic
alphabet</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mapach</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
